      en: "Mahatma Gandhi famously said 'India's soul lives in villages' reflecting his deep belief in village-centric development and Gram Swaraj (village self-rule). Gandhi argued that true India resided in its 700,000 villages, not in the few urban centers. He advocated for self-sufficient village republics where communities would produce their own needs, maintain local governance through panchayats, and preserve traditional crafts and agriculture. This philosophy was central to his vision of India's development, contrasting with Nehru's emphasis on industrialization and urbanization. Gandhi wrote extensively about village life in 'Hind Swaraj' (1909) and later publications, emphasizing that villages should be the foundation of India's political and economic structure. While Vinoba Bhave and Jayaprakash Narayan were influenced by Gandhian thought, the quote is distinctly Gandhi's.",
